ollower's amplitude is boosted and its contour apex is reinforced to fill the gap.\\\\\\\\n- Role metadata (`leader`, `follower`, `solo`, `tacet`) is correctly parsed and respected, with the rule only applying to voices explicitly tagged as followers.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Completeness\\\\\\\\nThe task is complete according to the acceptance criteria:\\\\\\\\n- `CallResponseRule` implemented in `render/rules/call_response.py`.\\\\\\\\n- Correct transformations for building and pausing states.\\\\\\\\n- Metadata role parsing covers all required keys and values.\\\\\\\\n- Comprehensive test suite in `tests/test_call_response.py` verifies both functional behavior and role-based filtering.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Consistency\\\\\\\\nThe implementation is consistent with other \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Tier 1\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" render rules in `src/cypherclaw/render/rules/` (e.g., `phrase_arch.py`, `articulation.py`). It uses the shared `Event` data model and follows the `role_is_eligible` contract established in `role_gate.py`. Although `PerformanceIntent` was mentioned in the spec, it is not yet present in the codebase (targeted for T-030), and the use of the `Event` model for these transformations is the correct adaptation for the current project state.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Security\\\\\\\\nNo security vulnerabilities or unsafe practices were introduced. The implementation consists of pure-function mathematical transformations on local data structures.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Quality\\\\\\\\nThe code quality is high, with clear documentation, clean dataclass abstractions, and robust role-parsing logic. The tests use Pearson correlation to verify complementarity, which is a rigorous approach for validating musical behavior.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Issues Found\\\\\\\\n- None.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Verdict: PASS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Notes for Lead Agent\\\\\\\\nThe implementation successfully realizes the call-response gating requirement. The adaptation to use the `Event` model in the absence of `Per